headline.main: AFFAIRS IN FRANCE.; The Queen of Roses--L'Autre Monde--Au Odd speculation--A French Forest in America--An Englishman in a Predicament--Last Night of Ristori, &c.

docs.lead_paragraph: THE NANTERRN ROSIERE. This year there was a crowd to seethe crowning of the Nanterre Rosiere. Her name was EUGENIE MESARD. In this family we have proof that virtue is hereditary, since the mother of EUGENIE was crowned in like manner twenty-five years ago. Nanterre is renowned for the virtue of its girls, and its cakes and butter.

headline.main: NEW-YORK CITY.; Fatal Accident. Killing Off our Children--By Authority. Fires.

docs.lead_paragraph: If the good people of New-York esteem it desirable to kill off nine-tenths of their small children, it must be confessed that they adopt measures admirably adapted to secure that result. If one walks in the upper Wards of the City any warm, cloudless day, the sense of sight and the sense of smell never fail to bear witness to their wisdom in this respect.

headline.main: A Woman Disguised in Man's clothes.

docs.lead_paragraph: From the Pittsburg Dispatch. I We notice in the papers mention of a young woman having been recently detected in the garb of a man among the workmen employed in a whip factory in Westfield. Mass.; and now that it can do no injury to expose her secret, we shall throw a little light upon her previous history--at least daringther three years' residence in this vicinity.

headline.main: KANSAS AFFAIRS.; FIRST DAY. The Kansas Emigrant Aid Societies Convention at Cleveland.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Delegates to the Kanasas Convention met at the Snos of Temperance Hall this morning, at 10 o'clock.. Convention was called to order by Mr. WILLIAM BARNES, of Albany, N. Y. in a brief, fireible and practical address; and upon motion W. H. STANLEY, of Cleveland, Ohio, was called to the Chair to act temporarily and EDWARD JAY ALLEN of Pitts burg, and D. W. BROOKS of Cleveland, to act as Secretaries.

headline.main: ARRIVAL OF MILLARD FILLMORE.; His Reception at the Collins Dock. Address of Ald. Briggs on Board the Atlantic. MR. FILLMORE'S REPLY.

docs.lead_paragraph: About 10 o'clock last night the firing of fifty guns from the Collins' Dock, at the foot of Canalstreet, North River, announced to all interested in the City, the arrival of the steamer Atlantic and Mr. MILLARD FILLMORE, Ex-President. In straggling scores a crowd began to assemble.
